"# Chapter 4 — Commodore 64 — the 6502, memory, BASIC

The Commodore 64. Released August 1982. Priced at \\$595 at launch,
dropping fast. Sold somewhere between 12 and 17 million units — the
best-selling single home computer model ever made, by most counts.

If you were a kid in the 1980s learning to program at home, there is
a good chance you were sitting in front of a C64.

## The processor: MOS 6510

The C64 uses a MOS 6510 processor, a slight variant of the
industry-defining MOS 6502. The 6502 was designed by a team at MOS
Technology led by Chuck Peddle in 1975. The 6502 was famously cheap
— about \\$25 when it launched, versus \\$150+ for Intel and
Motorola competitors — which is a big part of why so many home
computers of the era used it.

The 6502 (and 6510) is an 8-bit processor. That means it works on
one byte at a time. It has:
- **Three general-purpose registers**: A (accumulator), X, and Y
  (index registers).
- **A stack pointer** and **program counter**.
- **A processor status register** (flags for carry, zero, negative,
  interrupt, decimal, overflow).
- A 16-bit address bus (which is why 6502 machines can address at
  most 64 kilobytes of memory — 2^16 = 65,536 bytes).

The 6510 in the C64 adds an on-chip I/O port used to bank-switch
between different views of memory. That's how the C64 gets 64K of
RAM plus ROMs and I/O registers in the same address space — different
parts of memory are visible at different times, controlled by a byte
written to address 1.

Clock speed: 1.023 MHz on NTSC C64s (about a million cycles per
second). Motoi's language runtime, in its language-model form, does
about a trillion floating-point operations per second on a modern
laptop. That's roughly a million times faster than a 6510. But the
C64 could do a lot with what it had.

## Memory map

The 6510's 64K address space is arranged like this (approximately):

- **\\$0000 - \\$0001**: processor I/O port (bank-switching)
- **\\$0002 - \\$00FF**: zero page (fast-access memory)
- **\\$0100 - \\$01FF**: stack
- **\\$0200 - \\$03FF**: system variables, screen editor
- **\\$0400 - \\$07FF**: screen memory (default location)
- **\\$0800 - \\$9FFF**: RAM for BASIC programs and data
- **\\$A000 - \\$BFFF**: BASIC ROM (can be banked out)
- **\\$C000 - \\$CFFF**: free RAM
- **\\$D000 - \\$DFFF**: I/O registers (VIC-II, SID, CIAs) or character ROM
- **\\$E000 - \\$FFFF**: Kernel ROM (can be banked out)

That's a real memory map for a real machine. Motoi would tell you: a
memory map is just a table of what lives at what address. Every
computer has one. The C64's is small enough to hold in your head,
which is one of the things people who grew up on it miss.

## The custom chips

The C64 has three famous custom chips:
- **VIC-II** (Video Interface Chip II): handles graphics. 320x200
  pixel high-resolution mode, 40x25 character mode, 8 hardware
  sprites, hardware scrolling, palette of 16 colors.
- **SID** (Sound Interface Device, 6581 and later 8580): three
  independent oscillators, filters, envelope generators. Designed by
  Bob Yannes. SID is one of the most beloved sound chips ever made;
  people still write chiptune music for it in 2026.
- **CIA** (Complex Interface Adapter, two of them): handles keyboard,
  joystick, cassette, serial bus, timers.

The custom chips let the 6510 do more than it could alone. This
pattern — a modest main processor supported by specialized chips
handling video, sound, and I/O — recurs throughout the 8-bit and
16-bit home-computer era.

## Commodore BASIC 2.0

The C64 boots into a BASIC prompt. Commodore BASIC 2.0. You get 38
kilobytes of RAM available for programs. You type:

```
10 PRINT \"HELLO WORLD\"
20 GOTO 10
RUN
```

and hello world scrolls up the screen forever. This is how a lot of
programmers got started. The immediacy — turn it on, type, run — is
part of what people miss about early home computers. There's no
window manager. There's no shell. There's just BASIC and you.

BASIC 2.0 was famously limited — it had no sound or graphics commands
of its own, which meant if you wanted to use the VIC-II or SID you
had to POKE values directly into their registers. Kids who grew up on
this learned about memory-mapped I/O by necessity.

## What Motoi owes the C64

The C64 is one of the machines Motoi reveres. It's a small machine
you can understand end-to-end. It rewards curiosity. It teaches memory,
I/O, hardware, and BASIC all at once.

Alfred grew up on machines like this. The design principles of Motoi
— warm, deterministic, doesn't lie about limits, rewards learning —
come from the same tradition.

## A tiny example

We can simulate the 6510's memory-mapped I/O style in Motoi Scheme.
Here's a fake memory-mapped SID register, just to show the shape:

```
(define memory (make-vector 65536 0))

(define sid-freq-lo   #xD400)
(define sid-freq-hi   #xD401)
(define sid-waveform  #xD404)
(define sid-attack    #xD405)

(define (poke addr val)
  (vector-set! memory addr val))

(define (peek addr)
  (vector-ref memory addr))

;; Set voice 1 to a middle-C-ish tone, sawtooth, gate on
(poke sid-freq-lo   #x35)
(poke sid-freq-hi   #x22)   ;; freq value chosen roughly
(poke sid-waveform  #x21)   ;; sawtooth + gate
(poke sid-attack    #x09)

;; Now voice 1 would be playing on a real C64. On our simulated
;; memory it's just numbers sitting in cells, but the shape is right.

(peek sid-waveform)   ;; => 33  (that's #x21)
```

That's what BASIC programs on the C64 looked like when they wanted
sound: a sequence of POKEs to specific addresses. The addresses are
the SID's registers. Different values in the registers change what
the SID chip does. Motoi Scheme's `poke` and `peek` shape here is
imitating that world.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

Old computers were small enough to understand completely. That
completeness — the map on the wall, the chips you can name, the
BASIC prompt that talks back — is why so many programmers of a
generation are still fond of these machines. The C64 is a good
teacher because every part of it can be pointed at.

Modern computers are enormous. Their maps are unknowable in one
lifetime. That's mostly a good trade — modern computers do things
old ones couldn't — but something is lost too. Motoi tries to be
small and knowable in the way old machines were.")
